<i>Today's discussion</i>
<i>is postponed,</i>

7
00:01:11,112 --> 00:01:13,657
<i>as we have</i>
<i>a very special guest.</i>

8
00:01:13,699 --> 00:01:15,534
<i>He's played</i>
<i>an instrumental part</i>

9
00:01:15,576 --> 00:01:17,870
in the world debut
of the IBM PC,

10
00:01:17,912 --> 00:01:19,580
which is now
on the verge of becoming

11
00:01:19,621 --> 00:01:22,875
<i>the</i> industry standard
for corporate America.

12
00:01:22,917 --> 00:01:25,794
Please welcome
Mr. Joseph MacMillan.

13
00:01:25,836 --> 00:01:30,089
( students applauding )

14
00:01:30,131 --> 00:01:33,385
Let me start
by asking a question.

15
00:01:33,427 --> 00:01:36,388
How many
of you desire to be
computer engineers?

16
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:37,598
Hmm.

17
00:01:37,639 --> 00:01:39,224
<i>( music playing</i>
<i>faintly )</i>

18
00:01:39,266 --> 00:01:41,309
Oh-- I'm glad
you could join us.

19
00:01:43,311 --> 00:01:45,188
<i>Keep your hands up,</i>
<i>keep your hands up.</i>

20
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:47,482
Now I'm going to list off
several categories.

21
00:01:47,524 --> 00:01:49,568
When you hear a category
you don't have hands-on
experience in...

22
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:51,445
-<i> ( music stops ) </i>
- Put your hand down.

23
00:01:51,486 --> 00:01:53,113
<i>Software design.</i>

24
00:01:53,154 --> 00:01:55,741
<i>Hardware/software</i>
<i>integration.</i>

25
00:01:55,783 --> 00:01:58,326
Circuit design.
Microprocessing.

26
00:01:58,368 --> 00:02:02,372
Firmware design.
Very large-scale integration.

27
00:02:02,414 --> 00:02:04,374
- ( chuckles )
- Something funny?

28
00:02:04,416 --> 00:02:06,752
I don't think you really
know what that is.

29
00:02:06,794 --> 00:02:08,921
Why?

30
00:02:08,963 --> 00:02:10,881
Because nobody who knows
what it is calls it that.

31
00:02:10,923 --> 00:02:13,341
"VLSI."
How's that?

32
00:02:15,594 --> 00:02:17,846
Operating systems.

33
00:02:17,888 --> 00:02:21,892
P-ROM configuration
and PLC design.

34
00:02:23,226 --> 00:02:27,648
Personal computer design.
Very good.

35
00:02:27,689 --> 00:02:29,608
Now, tell me one thing
that will be true

36
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:31,110
about computers
10 years from now.

37
00:02:31,151 --> 00:02:34,113
Well, fully
intelligent machines

38
00:02:34,154 --> 00:02:36,782
will simulate the actions
of neurons more closely,
replicate--

39
00:02:36,824 --> 00:02:40,119
Okay, thanks.
You.

40
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:44,748
Uh, computers
will be connected together
across one network

41
00:02:44,790 --> 00:02:46,125
with a standard
protocol.

42
00:02:46,166 --> 00:02:49,336
- Like phone lines.
- Obviously phone lines.

43
00:02:49,377 --> 00:02:52,756
- What's your name?
- Cameron.

44
00:02:52,798 --> 00:02:54,842
Cameron Howe.

45
00:02:54,883 --> 00:02:57,052
<i>( music playing )</i>

46
00:02:57,094 --> 00:02:59,346
So, you graduate
this year.

47
00:02:59,387 --> 00:03:02,099
You land a job,
become a programmer for what,

48
00:03:02,141 --> 00:03:05,519
what do you wanna do?
Microcode? PCs? Video games?

49
00:03:05,560 --> 00:03:06,770
Do you need
a quarter?

50
00:03:07,980 --> 00:03:09,982
- Got it.
- Nice.

51
00:03:14,569 --> 00:03:17,781
I want to work
for Reagan's Strategic
Defense Initiative

52
00:03:17,823 --> 00:03:19,366
and put missiles
in space.

53
00:03:19,407 --> 00:03:21,827
Are you afraid to give me
a straight answer?

54
00:03:21,869 --> 00:03:25,497
-<i> ( video game rumbles ) </i>
- A straight answer?
Uh, let's see.

55
00:03:25,539 --> 00:03:28,750
Everything I'm studying here
is so totally 10 years ago

56
00:03:28,792 --> 00:03:31,003
that no one who matters
pays attention to anything I do.

57
00:03:31,045 --> 00:03:33,005
- I'm paying attention.
- Yeah, but do you matter?

58
00:03:33,047 --> 00:03:36,050
Hey, can we get
two more?

59
00:03:36,091 --> 00:03:37,926
Would you know
if I did?

60
00:03:37,968 --> 00:03:41,346
What is this anyway,
some kind of job interview?

61
00:03:41,388 --> 00:03:43,932
Maybe, maybe not.
Depends on you.

62
00:03:44,975 --> 00:03:47,268
<i>( machine clattering )</i>

63
00:03:47,310 --> 00:03:48,687
You still haven't
answered my question.

64
00:03:48,729 --> 00:03:50,814
Does it even matter
what I want to do?

65
00:03:50,856 --> 00:03:52,649
God, this is an industry
built on people

66
00:03:52,691 --> 00:03:54,860
ripping off each other's
boring-ass ideas.

67
00:03:54,902 --> 00:03:58,405
SCP rips off CP/M,
Microsoft rips off SCP.

68
00:03:58,446 --> 00:03:59,948
Oh, IBM rips off
everybody, right?

69
00:03:59,990 --> 00:04:01,449
You've got
a lot of excuses.

70
00:04:01,491 --> 00:04:03,202
And you work for IBM.

71
00:04:03,243 --> 00:04:06,621
Hey, computers could be more.
They should be.

72
00:04:06,663 --> 00:04:10,500
You build counting machines,
the same thing you've done
for the last 70 years.

73
00:04:10,542 --> 00:04:13,253
I don't work for IBM.

74
00:04:21,553 --> 00:04:23,055
( bangs )

75
00:04:27,601 --> 00:04:30,478
( moaning )

76
00:04:52,126 --> 00:04:53,585
Uh!

77
00:04:55,629 --> 00:04:56,922
( thumps )

78
00:04:56,964 --> 00:04:59,382
( panting )

79
00:05:13,147 --> 00:05:15,607
( grunting )

80
00:05:17,276 --> 00:05:20,403
This doesn't mean
you get the job.

81
00:05:25,033 --> 00:05:27,577
Wow.

82
00:05:28,745 --> 00:05:31,039
You mean
we're not in love?

83
00:05:39,173 --> 00:05:40,966
