-<i> ( keys jingle ) </i>
-<i> ( lock clicks )</i>

85
00:06:13,081 --> 00:06:15,209
Guard:
<i>Clark.</i>

86
00:06:22,716 --> 00:06:26,594
-<i> ( two-way radio chatter ) </i>
-<i> ( gate buzzes )</i>

87
00:06:30,974 --> 00:06:32,391
Man on radio: 
<i>Clear the gate.</i>

88
00:06:39,774 --> 00:06:41,735
Ain't no jail cell
can hold me.

89
00:06:43,028 --> 00:06:45,906
Come on.

90
00:06:49,659 --> 00:06:51,703
You didn't have to
bring the kids.

91
00:06:51,745 --> 00:06:53,872
I think I did.

92
00:07:04,174 --> 00:07:07,635
Look, I had
one too many drinks.

93
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:10,013
It got away from me.

94
00:07:10,055 --> 00:07:13,850
It won't happen again.

95
00:07:13,892 --> 00:07:16,270
Sorry.

96
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:21,858
You still
have a job?

97
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:24,361
Of course I do.

98
00:07:24,403 --> 00:07:27,197
They could care less
about me anyway.

99
00:07:31,118 --> 00:07:33,412
Remember at the demo

100
00:07:33,453 --> 00:07:35,956
when we went to turn it on
and it wouldn't turn on?

101
00:07:35,997 --> 00:07:38,250
Gordon...

102
00:07:38,292 --> 00:07:43,838
It's like, 1979 was good,
but then 1980 came

103
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:47,717
and it was like, whoa...

104
00:07:47,759 --> 00:07:51,221
what happened,
you know?

105
00:07:51,263 --> 00:07:55,309
What I know is that
you need to be at work
in four hours.

106
00:07:55,350 --> 00:07:57,894
Four.

107
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:03,233
Then your dad--
your dad said,

108
00:08:03,275 --> 00:08:05,860
"We can't lend you
any more."

109
00:08:05,902 --> 00:08:08,280
And he wasn't
being mean.

110
00:08:08,322 --> 00:08:12,200
He was just
in his kitchen
looking at me,

111
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:16,371
and I said,
"Okay, Gary."

112
00:08:16,413 --> 00:08:18,081
You're drunk,
so the best thing

113
00:08:18,123 --> 00:08:21,418
you could do right now
is to shut up.

114
00:08:25,255 --> 00:08:27,715
- ( clicks )
- I know what IBM is.

115
00:08:29,426 --> 00:08:31,803
I also know
what IBM ain't,

116
00:08:31,845 --> 00:08:33,972
and everything
that ain't IBM is cheaper,
faster, and better,

117
00:08:34,014 --> 00:08:35,640
and that's what
this company lives by.

118
00:08:35,682 --> 00:08:37,225
Well, John, that's
what Hitachi thought.

119
00:08:37,267 --> 00:08:38,893
And Burroughs and NCR

120
00:08:38,935 --> 00:08:40,812
and Honeywell
and Control Data.

121
00:08:40,854 --> 00:08:42,897
No, I know
all the companies
that IBM has crushed,

122
00:08:42,939 --> 00:08:44,649
and Cardiff Electric
ain't one of 'em.
It won't be.

123
00:08:44,691 --> 00:08:46,318
You sound pretty sure
about that.

124
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:48,987
( laughs )
Look at you.

125
00:08:49,029 --> 00:08:53,241
Same suit,
different tie.

126
00:08:53,283 --> 00:08:56,995
You know, Dallas is a long way
from Armonk, New York, son.

127
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:59,039
- That's no accident.
- I couldn't agree
with you more.

128
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:01,875
Maybe I'm a guy who's done
doing business like that.

129
00:09:01,916 --> 00:09:03,960
Maybe I see Cardiff Electric
as a mid-major

130
00:09:04,002 --> 00:09:05,337
ready to take the jump

131
00:09:05,379 --> 00:09:07,381
and myself as the
heavy hitter you need

132
00:09:07,422 --> 00:09:11,176
to legitimize your sales force,
this company, this region.

133
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:14,804
I just need somebone
to come in here and blow
the balls off the numbers, Joe.

134
00:09:14,846 --> 00:09:17,682
I will tell you this--
it's systems software,
straight up.

135
00:09:17,724 --> 00:09:20,060
No application,
no next-gen PC garbage.

136
00:09:20,101 --> 00:09:22,312
It ain't sexy, but it
sure as hell makes us
some serious money.

137
00:09:22,354 --> 00:09:24,898
- Then I'm your guy.
- ( scoffs )
Don't know if I see it.

138
00:09:24,939 --> 00:09:27,067
You got East Coast corporate
written all over ya.

139
00:09:27,108 --> 00:09:29,861
Don't like
East Coast corporate.

140
00:09:29,903 --> 00:09:32,989
Hell, hotshot, you didn't
bring in a damn resume.

141
00:09:36,826 --> 00:09:38,495
<i>( briefcase</i>
<i>latches click )</i>

142
00:09:41,122 --> 00:09:43,958
- And what is this?
What am I looking at?
- My W-2.

143
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,295
- Box one is my last
reported income at IBM.
- Whoo-hoo.

144
00:09:47,337 --> 00:09:50,382
It's also what 200%
of quota looks like.

145
00:09:51,841 --> 00:09:53,510
The golden circle.

146
00:09:53,552 --> 00:09:57,680
I'll break numbers.
I always do.

147
00:09:58,890 --> 00:10:02,060
( laughs )

148
00:10:02,102 --> 00:10:05,063
You answer to me.
I'm SVP of sales,

149
00:10:05,105 --> 00:10:09,234
so you're dog shit around here
until you close a deal.

150
00:10:09,276 --> 00:10:11,528
- Do you understand?
- I do.

151
00:10:11,570 --> 00:10:15,282
"I do."
Good.

152
00:10:15,323 --> 00:10:18,034
Well, we're married.

153
00:10:20,328 --> 00:10:22,539
You may now go break
your numbers, darlin'.

154
00:10:52,152 --> 00:10:54,488
Woman on radio:
<i>...free and clear through</i>
<i>Lewisville and Carrollton,</i>

155
00:10:54,529 --> 00:10:55,489
<i>but starting to slow down...</i>

156
00:10:55,530 --> 00:10:58,241
<i>( engine belt squeaking )</i>

157
00:10:58,283 --> 00:11:00,243
Hey.

158
00:11:00,285 --> 00:11:02,370
( honks horn )

159
00:11:02,412 --> 00:11:04,247
A-16.

160
00:11:06,333 --> 00:11:09,669
Hey, that's me.
That's my spot, A-16.

161
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:18,261
Woman on radio:
<i>...high from Love Field today</i>
<i>is 86...</i>

162
00:11:37,489 --> 00:11:39,574
( clicks )

163
00:11:43,370 --> 00:11:46,122
MacMillan:
A-16!

164
00:11:46,164 --> 00:11:49,209
A-16.

165
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:53,588
- You're my SE
for this sales call.
- Oh, fantastic.

166
00:11:53,630 --> 00:11:57,842
We'll take my car,
it's closer.

167
00:11:57,884 --> 00:11:59,594
MacMillan:
The truth is, our systems

168
00:11:59,636 --> 00:12:02,347
are outperforming
every top seller
in the market.

169
00:12:02,389 --> 00:12:04,307
- What about IBM?
- IBM is IBM,

170
00:12:04,349 --> 00:12:06,017
but we're neck and neck
and we're cheaper.

171
00:12:06,059 --> 00:12:09,187
Technically.
The difference in cost
is negligible.

172
00:12:09,229 --> 00:12:12,357
It just seems you guys
at Cardiff think you've built
yourselves a fancy race car

173
00:12:12,399 --> 00:12:13,858
that deserves
an outrageous price tag.

174
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:16,152
And we get no
Big Blue guarantee.

175
00:12:16,194 --> 00:12:17,612
I don't think
there is such a thing.

176
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:19,906
Well, they
had me fooled.

177
00:12:19,947 --> 00:12:21,991
- ( man laughs )
- Me, too.

178
00:12:24,369 --> 00:12:25,995
I worked here.

179
00:12:27,372 --> 00:12:29,165
I grew up there.

180
00:12:29,207 --> 00:12:33,127
And I was
brought up to believe
that the work we did,

181
00:12:33,169 --> 00:12:35,963
the things we built were
the singular contribution
to computers

182
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:37,882
that history
would remember.

183
00:12:37,924 --> 00:12:40,051
And I believed it
for a long time.

184
00:12:40,093 --> 00:12:43,513
For a long time,
it was true.

185
00:12:45,098 --> 00:12:48,727
Nobody ever got fired
for buying an IBM, right?

186
00:12:49,977 --> 00:12:53,398
What a fearful way
to do business.

187
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:55,900
You've made
just enough safe choices

188
00:12:55,942 --> 00:12:59,237
to stay alive,
but not enough to matter.

189
00:12:59,279 --> 00:13:01,740
Is that
what you want?

190
00:13:01,780 --> 00:13:04,909
You can be more.

191
00:13:04,951 --> 00:13:07,995
You want to be more,
don't you?

192
00:13:09,830 --> 00:13:12,417
The window of opportunity
is closing.

193
00:13:12,459 --> 00:13:15,169
This is your chance.

194
00:13:15,211 --> 00:13:17,756
<i>This is not</i>
<i>about not losing.</i>

195
00:13:17,796 --> 00:13:22,510
This is about you
finally having the confidence

196
00:13:22,552 --> 00:13:27,014
to walk out on the ledge
and know that you're
not going to fall.

197
00:13:28,807 --> 00:13:32,103
Are we still talking about
systems software here?

198
00:13:32,145 --> 00:13:34,230
Amen, let's get
this guy another drink.

199
00:13:34,272 --> 00:13:37,609
I'm not going to apologize
for caring about your business,

200
00:13:37,651 --> 00:13:39,444
even if the people
who work for you don't.

201
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:43,698
I'll ask you
one more time.

202
00:13:43,740 --> 00:13:47,034
Are you ready
to be more?

203
00:14:00,298 --> 00:14:04,678
- There's also free install--
- Gordon, please.

204
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:12,560
I'll think about it.

205
00:14:23,822 --> 00:14:26,407
Look, it's better
than a flat-out no.

206
00:14:29,661 --> 00:14:33,331
Hey, man, look,
Applied Data hasn't bought
jack-all from anyone in years.

207
00:14:33,373 --> 00:14:35,082
You did a solid job
explaining the software,

208
00:14:35,124 --> 00:14:37,335
but I need you
to do me one favor.

209
00:14:37,377 --> 00:14:39,086
Okay.

210
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:41,047
Next time I move to close,
this is what you do.

211
00:14:41,088 --> 00:14:45,134
- Okay, what?
- You<i> shut up!</i>

212
00:14:47,428 --> 00:14:48,763
<i>"Lodi" playing</i>

213
00:14:48,805 --> 00:14:52,559
<i>♪ The man</i>
<i>from the magazine ♪</i>

214
00:14:52,600 --> 00:14:54,060
<i>♪ Said I was</i>
<i>on my way... ♪</i>

215
00:14:54,101 --> 00:14:57,146
- Hey.
- Hey, Mom.

216
00:14:57,188 --> 00:14:58,898
Come here,
you little monkeys.
Give me my kisses.

217
00:15:01,693 --> 00:15:03,403
Thank you.
Go play.

218
00:15:03,444 --> 00:15:07,365
<i>♪ Came into town,</i>
<i>a one-night stand ♪</i>

219
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:11,244
-<i> ♪ Looks like my plans</i>
<i>fell through... ♪ </i>
- It's soda.

220
00:15:11,285 --> 00:15:13,371
<i>♪ Oh, Lord ♪</i>

221
00:15:13,413 --> 00:15:16,332
<i>♪ Stuck in Lodi again... ♪</i>

222
00:15:18,459 --> 00:15:20,795
Daughter:
<i>Mom, Speak &amp; Spell's</i>
<i>not working.</i>

223
00:15:20,837 --> 00:15:22,463
Well, what's wrong
with it?

224
00:15:22,505 --> 00:15:24,465
- It won't turn on.
- Joanie did it.

225
00:15:24,507 --> 00:15:27,385
Uh-uh, Haley did it.
She was playing with
her blocks--

226
00:15:27,427 --> 00:15:29,220
Let's see.

227
00:15:29,262 --> 00:15:33,057
<i>♪ ...had a dollar</i>
<i>for every song I've sung... ♪</i>

228
00:15:33,099 --> 00:15:35,059
Joanie's Speak &amp; Spell
won't turn on.

229
00:15:35,101 --> 00:15:38,897
Joanie:
Pressing "on"
makes it go.

230
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:41,148
Okay.

231
00:15:41,190 --> 00:15:44,151
- Are you gonna fix it?
- I'm gonna try.

232
00:15:44,193 --> 00:15:46,780
<i>Did it give you</i>
<i>any good words?</i>

233
00:15:46,821 --> 00:15:48,656
Did it stump you
at all?

234
00:15:48,698 --> 00:15:50,700
No.

235
00:15:50,742 --> 00:15:52,493
Okay.

236
00:15:52,535 --> 00:15:54,829
Joanie: 
<i>She was throwing</i>
<i>her blocks at it.</i>

237
00:15:54,871 --> 00:15:57,540
Haley:
<i>But you did it.</i>
<i>You were pressing "on."</i>

