470
00:29:56,128 --> 00:29:58,756
I-I thought you weren't
gonna be back till Monday.

471
00:29:58,797 --> 00:30:02,092
It is Monday.

472
00:30:02,134 --> 00:30:04,762
Haley's sick.
I figured she caught
whatever you had,

473
00:30:04,803 --> 00:30:07,806
but looking at you now,
I can tell that you're
not sick at all.

474
00:30:09,391 --> 00:30:12,728
Would you please tell me
that you didn't buy all this?

475
00:30:12,770 --> 00:30:15,731
- Maybe I can help explain--
- I'd like to speak
to my husband...

476
00:30:15,773 --> 00:30:17,107
privately.

477
00:30:27,409 --> 00:30:29,662
- Gordon:<i> Honey,</i>
<i>just let me explain-- </i>
-<i> I really don't understand.</i>

478
00:30:29,703 --> 00:30:31,705
- Let me just
defend myself here.
- Why would you lie to me?

479
00:30:31,747 --> 00:30:34,458
- Hold on, I did not lie
to you about anything.
- You did, you lied.

480
00:30:34,500 --> 00:30:36,293
- No, I did not lie to you.
- Gordon, this is going
backwards.

481
00:30:36,335 --> 00:30:38,128
This right here,
this is what I want
to do with my life!

482
00:30:38,170 --> 00:30:41,256
Yes, but don't you realize
what you're risking?

483
00:30:41,298 --> 00:30:43,634
Don't you realize
what you have now?

484
00:30:46,178 --> 00:30:48,639
Well, it's
not enough.

485
00:30:48,681 --> 00:30:51,350
Okay? I'm sorry,
it's not enough.

486
00:30:54,436 --> 00:30:57,481
Okay.

487
00:30:57,523 --> 00:31:00,233
Well, it always
has been enough for me.

488
00:31:00,275 --> 00:31:01,860
Come on, Donna,
don't be like that.

489
00:31:01,901 --> 00:31:03,529
But I guess I never
had the burden of believing

490
00:31:03,570 --> 00:31:06,072
that I was some
misunderstood genius.

491
00:31:08,116 --> 00:31:09,451
<i>( car door closes )</i>

492
00:31:12,245 --> 00:31:14,665
Donna:
<i>Let's put you to bed.</i>

493
00:31:14,707 --> 00:31:17,626
- John?
- Nope.

494
00:31:17,668 --> 00:31:19,753
I'm sorry, but I think
you'll wanna take this.

495
00:31:19,795 --> 00:31:21,338
<i>Mama makin'</i>
<i>pork chops tonight.</i>

496
00:31:21,380 --> 00:31:23,131
It's IBM.

497
00:31:32,516 --> 00:31:34,518
<i>( button clicks )</i>

498
00:31:34,560 --> 00:31:36,687
Bosworth here.

499
00:31:36,729 --> 00:31:41,941
John, it's Dale Butler,
Senior Vice President of Sales,
North America.

500
00:31:44,236 --> 00:31:46,572
What can I
do you for, Dale?

501
00:31:46,613 --> 00:31:51,535
- You got one of
my boys down there.
- Why, yes, we do.

502
00:31:51,577 --> 00:31:53,203
MacMillan.
Uh-huh.

503
00:31:53,245 --> 00:31:55,539
Interesting fella.

504
00:31:55,581 --> 00:31:58,876
( Dale chuckles )
I guess I can say it's
good to know he's alive.

505
00:31:58,917 --> 00:32:00,878
How so?

506
00:32:00,919 --> 00:32:04,339
<i>Joe walked out the front door</i>
<i>of our offices last March.</i>

507
00:32:04,381 --> 00:32:06,174
And?

508
00:32:06,216 --> 00:32:07,593
And he never came back.

509
00:32:12,723 --> 00:32:15,308
You lost me, Dale.

510
00:32:15,350 --> 00:32:17,603
No one has seen or heard
from Joe MacMillan

511
00:32:17,644 --> 00:32:19,312
in more than a year.

512
00:32:19,354 --> 00:32:20,898
<i>We even filed</i>
<i>police reports.</i>

513
00:32:20,939 --> 00:32:22,900
<i>Up until we caught wind</i>
<i>he was working for you,</i>

514
00:32:22,941 --> 00:32:26,737
we believed the worst,
but here we are.

515
00:32:26,779 --> 00:32:28,906
<i>He's damaged goods, John.</i>

516
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:32,409
<i>I wish I could've warned you,</i>
<i>but now it might be too late.</i>

517
00:32:32,451 --> 00:32:35,370
How so?

518
00:32:35,412 --> 00:32:38,916
I'm here with Rebecca Taylor,
our in-house legal counsel.

519
00:32:41,334 --> 00:32:45,631
Hi, John.
We've got a problem.

520
00:32:59,394 --> 00:33:01,354
- You two-- sit down.
-<i> ( door closes )</i>

521
00:33:03,941 --> 00:33:05,442
<i>This here</i>
<i>is Nathan Cardiff.</i>

522
00:33:05,484 --> 00:33:07,235
<i>He owns the company</i>
<i>you destroyed.</i>

523
00:33:07,277 --> 00:33:09,279
<i>We just got done with</i>
<i>a two-and-a-half-hour jaw</i>

524
00:33:09,321 --> 00:33:10,739
with IBM's legal team,

525
00:33:10,781 --> 00:33:12,491
including your old boss,
Dale Butler.

526
00:33:12,532 --> 00:33:13,700
Oh, yeah?
How's he doing?

527
00:33:15,911 --> 00:33:17,746
Oh, he's doing
pretty splendid,

528
00:33:17,788 --> 00:33:20,666
given the fact
that Big Blue is gonna
liquidate this company

529
00:33:20,707 --> 00:33:23,794
to the tune
of several dozen million
dollars in legal damages

530
00:33:23,836 --> 00:33:26,463
because two
idiot children
in our employ

531
00:33:26,505 --> 00:33:28,757
decided to rip off
their flagship product.

532
00:33:28,799 --> 00:33:30,467
Sir, that wasn't
the idea.

533
00:33:30,509 --> 00:33:32,010
We did this
solely on our own.

534
00:33:32,051 --> 00:33:33,595
It turns out
that doesn't matter--

535
00:33:33,637 --> 00:33:36,556
and, believe me,
we tried to feed you
to the wolves, boys.

536
00:33:36,598 --> 00:33:38,642
But because
MacMillan here
worked at IBM

537
00:33:38,684 --> 00:33:41,060
and you two were
in our employ at the time
of your little project,

538
00:33:41,102 --> 00:33:43,814
that project is ours now,
for better or worse.

539
00:33:43,856 --> 00:33:45,607
Worse,
in this case.

540
00:33:45,649 --> 00:33:48,443
Butler and that woman Taylor
are headed down here tomorrow.

541
00:33:48,485 --> 00:33:51,571
Sir, how the hell
did IBM find out
about this?

542
00:33:51,613 --> 00:33:53,365
I told them.

543
00:33:55,575 --> 00:33:57,661
Hey! Hey!

544
00:33:57,703 --> 00:33:59,955
That's how you
force their hand?
You call IBM?

545
00:33:59,997 --> 00:34:01,456
Just let
everybody cool off.

546
00:34:01,498 --> 00:34:04,001
This is exactly what my wife--
Joe, look at me.

547
00:34:04,042 --> 00:34:08,714
I'm not like you, okay?
I have a wife, kids,
a mortgage, okay?

548
00:34:08,755 --> 00:34:12,300
I was fine until you threw
that stupid article in my face
and gave me some--

549
00:34:12,342 --> 00:34:13,969
What? What did
I give you, Gordon?

550
00:34:14,011 --> 00:34:17,389
- Oh, go to hell, Joe.
- Good! Get angry, get angry!

551
00:34:17,430 --> 00:34:19,683
Feel something,
like you did in
that garage,

552
00:34:19,725 --> 00:34:22,811
because this
is the only way
we get what we want.

553
00:34:22,853 --> 00:34:25,605
- There is no "we," Joe.
- There is now.

554
00:34:25,647 --> 00:34:28,483
I was at COMDEX
two years ago.

555
00:34:28,525 --> 00:34:32,905
I saw the Symphonic demo.
It was ahead of its time.

556
00:34:32,946 --> 00:34:36,324
That was then,
this is now--
and a year from now,

557
00:34:36,366 --> 00:34:38,911
you're gonna thank me.
You're a builder, Gordon.

558
00:34:38,952 --> 00:34:41,413
No, I'm not, okay?
Not anymore.

559
00:34:41,454 --> 00:34:43,540
All right?
Get that through
your head.

560
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:53,299
Hey.

561
00:34:55,802 --> 00:34:58,346
- Yeah.
- Yes.

562
00:35:00,599 --> 00:35:02,768
I figured
you needed a break.

563
00:35:02,809 --> 00:35:04,561
Joanie:
<i>Daddy, you fixed it!</i>

564
00:35:04,603 --> 00:35:06,772
Yeah, well, turn it on.

565
00:35:06,813 --> 00:35:10,275
<i>( toy beeps )</i>
<i>Hello, Joanie.</i>

566
00:35:10,316 --> 00:35:12,736
How'd you get it
to say my name?

567
00:35:12,778 --> 00:35:16,406
Well, I programmed it.
Now spell something for me.

568
00:35:16,448 --> 00:35:18,324
( both giggle )

569
00:35:18,366 --> 00:35:22,746
Electronic voice:
<i>D-A-D-D-Y.</i>

570
00:35:22,788 --> 00:35:24,414
What's that spell?

571
00:35:29,962 --> 00:35:32,380
<i>( dishes clatter )</i>

572
00:35:32,422 --> 00:35:35,842
Look, I've been awful.

573
00:35:35,884 --> 00:35:38,553
I'm sorry.

574
00:35:40,472 --> 00:35:42,599
I know you think
you need this.

575
00:35:42,641 --> 00:35:46,269
And whatever it is,
I'm pretty sure
I can't stop you.

576
00:35:46,311 --> 00:35:50,482
Yeah, I know.
I've already stopped, okay?

577
00:35:50,523 --> 00:35:56,362
Computers, my job--
none of that matters.

578
00:35:56,404 --> 00:35:58,573
Not without you.

579
00:36:13,171 --> 00:36:14,965
Build it.

580
00:36:16,508 --> 00:36:19,511
Whatever it is you're
dreaming of, build it.

581
00:36:19,552 --> 00:36:23,389
I know you
can make it great.

582
00:36:27,144 --> 00:36:30,063
But here's the deal.

583
00:36:30,105 --> 00:36:32,774
You wanna partner
with Joe MacMillan...

584
00:36:35,527 --> 00:36:38,488
then you partner
with me and this family.

585
00:36:38,530 --> 00:36:40,699
Yeah.

586
00:36:40,740 --> 00:36:42,408
Deal.

587
00:36:49,958 --> 00:36:51,960
Why can't we fire
these peckerheads?

588
00:36:52,002 --> 00:36:53,503
Because then you'll
lose this lawsuit.

589
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:55,088
Fire them,
shelve their work,

590
00:36:55,130 --> 00:36:56,589
you're essentially
admitting guilt.

591
00:36:56,631 --> 00:36:58,842
Okay, so what's
the solution, Barry?

592
00:36:58,884 --> 00:37:00,385
We legitimize
the project.

593
00:37:00,426 --> 00:37:02,387
- What?
- Go the other way.

594
00:37:02,428 --> 00:37:04,347
We say Cardiff Electric
as a company

595
00:37:04,389 --> 00:37:06,224
has been pursuing
PC development all along.

596
00:37:06,265 --> 00:37:07,851
I don't see how the hell
that'd solve any--

597
00:37:07,893 --> 00:37:09,686
You take Clark's findings
on the BIOS chip,

598
00:37:09,728 --> 00:37:11,855
you tell an engineer
to build a unit that operates
and performs

599
00:37:11,897 --> 00:37:14,691
in exactly the same way,
but you don't tell him
how to do it.

600
00:37:14,733 --> 00:37:16,359
Hell, I don't think
we have one engineer

601
00:37:16,401 --> 00:37:18,028
capable of building
a BIOS from scratch

602
00:37:18,070 --> 00:37:20,030
other than "Sonny Bono"
over here.

603
00:37:20,072 --> 00:37:22,866
And you can't use him
or any other engineer
we currently employ.

604
00:37:22,908 --> 00:37:26,619
- So we have to hire?
- Yes, someone who doesn't
know us or IBM

605
00:37:26,661 --> 00:37:29,039
and certainly hasn't seen
the contents of this binder.

606
00:37:29,081 --> 00:37:31,166
Essentially,
all the law stipulates

607
00:37:31,208 --> 00:37:33,752
is that he can't be hands-on
in the actual chip creation.

608
00:37:33,793 --> 00:37:35,712
- And we can't fire them.
- Barry:<i> No, not right now.</i>

609
00:37:35,754 --> 00:37:39,591
So we get out of this
by actually building
a PC clone?

610
00:37:39,632 --> 00:37:42,719
This is your brilliant idea
to save our hides, Barry?

611
00:37:42,761 --> 00:37:44,721
For God's sake, man!

612
00:37:44,763 --> 00:37:47,140
No.

613
00:37:47,182 --> 00:37:50,560
Actually,
it was MacMillan's.

614
00:37:57,234 --> 00:37:59,819
You son of a bitch.

615
00:37:59,861 --> 00:38:01,988
Now, why didn't you tell me
about this yesterday?

616
00:38:02,030 --> 00:38:04,074
I needed you
to exhaust your options

617
00:38:04,116 --> 00:38:06,076
so that you would
take this one seriously.

618
00:38:06,118 --> 00:38:08,912
Do you know
how many futures you're
toying with here, son?

619
00:38:08,954 --> 00:38:12,707
Selling systems software,
I probably would've made you
a couple hundred thousand--

620
00:38:12,749 --> 00:38:15,710
( screams )
You listen to me, boy!
You listen to me!

621
00:38:17,837 --> 00:38:20,840
I admire
your tenacity,

622
00:38:20,882 --> 00:38:25,720
but I draw the line
at you claiming that
you did me a favor.

623
00:38:29,015 --> 00:38:31,935
Don't screw this up.

624
00:38:31,977 --> 00:38:35,772
'Cause in Texas, you put
a man's livelihood on the line
and you don't follow through,

625
00:38:35,814 --> 00:38:37,941
there's not gonna be
another new job

626
00:38:37,983 --> 00:38:40,152
'cause ain't nobody
gonna be able to find
where you're buried.

627
00:38:41,611 --> 00:38:43,863
You've got something
to say, Gordon?

628
00:38:44,990 --> 00:38:47,033
No. No, sir.

629
00:38:47,075 --> 00:38:49,035
Bosworth:
<i>Where are we gonna find</i>
<i>this new engineer?</i>

630
00:38:49,077 --> 00:38:51,871
We needed him yesterday.
IBM legal's here first
thing tomorrow.

631
00:38:51,913 --> 00:38:53,832
- I need time
to vet a candidate.
- Barry:<i> We don't have time.</i>

632
00:38:53,873 --> 00:38:55,959
You think IBM
is just sitting around
on their asses?

633
00:38:56,001 --> 00:38:58,336
Who do we have
right now, huh?

634
00:38:58,377 --> 00:39:00,839
<i>Who do we have right now?</i>
<i>( slams desk )</i>

635
00:39:06,094 --> 00:39:08,180
<i>"Wanna Be Manor" plays</i>

636
00:39:08,221 --> 00:39:10,015
<i>♪ I ended up</i>
<i>at the Wannabe Manor ♪</i>

637
00:39:10,056 --> 00:39:11,933
<i>♪ Wannabe Manor,</i>
<i>what a place to be ♪</i>

638
00:39:11,975 --> 00:39:15,103
<i>♪ Wannabe Manor,</i>
<i>is not for me... ♪</i>

639
00:39:15,145 --> 00:39:16,354
( bangs )

640
00:39:18,064 --> 00:39:19,941
<i>♪ I walked in the door,</i>
<i>pee on the floor ♪</i>

641
00:39:19,983 --> 00:39:21,693
<i>♪ Looked on the floor,</i>
<i>spotted a whore ♪</i>

642
00:39:21,734 --> 00:39:23,569
<i>♪ Drugs and filth</i>
<i>are all around ♪</i>

643
00:39:23,611 --> 00:39:25,905
<i>♪ No clean dishes</i>
<i>can be found ♪</i>

644
00:39:25,947 --> 00:39:27,824
<i>♪ If you thought</i>
<i>your nightmares were scary ♪</i>

645
00:39:27,866 --> 00:39:29,868
<i>♪ Wait till you meet</i>
<i>the ho called Jeri... ♪</i>

646
00:39:29,909 --> 00:39:32,620
Next game.

647
00:39:32,662 --> 00:39:35,207
-<i> ♪ It's her spreading legs</i>
<i>and her female perfume... ♪ </i>
- ( game buzzes )

648
00:39:35,248 --> 00:39:37,834
-<i> ( quarter clatters ) </i>
- What the hell? You've
been on for over an hour.

649
00:39:37,876 --> 00:39:39,836
Hey.

650
00:39:39,878 --> 00:39:41,587
Hey.

651
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:43,173
Get your hands
off me, man.

652
00:39:43,215 --> 00:39:45,175
We're getting complaints.

653
00:39:46,885 --> 00:39:49,179
Unbelievable.
You're gone.

654
00:39:49,221 --> 00:39:51,306
Go!

655
00:39:51,348 --> 00:39:52,807
Later, spooky bitch.

656
00:39:55,060 --> 00:39:58,271
- Arcade employee:<i> Hey! </i>
- What?

657
00:39:58,313 --> 00:40:01,774
- That's enough!
- Put me down!

658
00:40:01,816 --> 00:40:03,776
- Come on!
- Let go of me!

659
00:40:03,818 --> 00:40:04,986
Go!

660
00:40:05,028 --> 00:40:06,321
( yells )

661
00:40:08,240 --> 00:40:10,367
- Fascist!
- ( coins clatter )

662
00:40:12,994 --> 00:40:14,412
God.

663
00:40:16,915 --> 00:40:19,251
Oh, Jesus.

664
00:40:21,044 --> 00:40:22,879
No.

665
00:40:24,881 --> 00:40:26,091
What?

666
00:40:27,884 --> 00:40:29,344
Great.

667
00:40:32,931 --> 00:40:35,392
<i>( patrons chattering )</i>

668
00:40:38,436 --> 00:40:39,812
You know
I screwed him, right?

669
00:40:39,854 --> 00:40:42,565
Let's be adult
about this.

670
00:40:42,607 --> 00:40:44,234
You love talking down
to me, don't you?

671
00:40:44,276 --> 00:40:46,444
Look, there are a thousand
other engineers we can get.

672
00:40:46,485 --> 00:40:49,322
Preferably one
you haven't bedded down with.

673
00:40:49,364 --> 00:40:54,202
- Who are you again?
- I'm the guy who figured out
the boot code in four days.

674
00:40:54,244 --> 00:40:57,247
- What have you done?
- You heard him-- a thousand
other engineers.

675
00:40:57,289 --> 00:40:59,624
No.

676
00:40:59,665 --> 00:41:01,918
You need me, otherwise
you wouldn't be here.

677
00:41:01,960 --> 00:41:04,045
What do you want?

678
00:41:04,087 --> 00:41:07,424
I want you to go dangle
your little opportunity
in someone else's face.

679
00:41:07,465 --> 00:41:10,927
- Then why are you still here?
- I wanted to see what I was so
wrong about the first time.

680
00:41:10,969 --> 00:41:12,429
I regret that happened.

681
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:14,722
I'm sorry you feel bad
for hurting my feelings,

682
00:41:14,764 --> 00:41:16,808
but don't worry,
you didn't.

683
00:41:16,849 --> 00:41:18,935
It wasn't
supposed to be personal.
I was scouting you.

684
00:41:18,977 --> 00:41:21,646
Scouting you
for this exact moment.

685
00:41:21,687 --> 00:41:22,855
- Humph.
- No, wait.

686
00:41:24,774 --> 00:41:28,111
This is too important
to get wrong.

687
00:41:28,153 --> 00:41:29,946
"No one who matters
pays attention," right?

688
00:41:29,988 --> 00:41:31,281
Okay, stop selling me.

689
00:41:31,323 --> 00:41:33,116
I don't need you.

690
00:41:33,158 --> 00:41:34,909
You think
I don't see it?

691
00:41:34,951 --> 00:41:36,453
This takes off,
I write my own ticket,

692
00:41:36,494 --> 00:41:39,831
but if it goes wrong,
I'm a college dropout

693
00:41:39,872 --> 00:41:42,208
repairing VCRs
for $3.25 an hour,

694
00:41:42,250 --> 00:41:44,336
so forgive me
for weighing my options.

695
00:41:44,377 --> 00:41:46,296
See?

696
00:41:46,338 --> 00:41:48,006
Now you're thinking
like a professional.

697
00:41:51,468 --> 00:41:53,970
How much money
would you give me?

698
00:41:54,012 --> 00:41:57,807
Junior engineer,
no experience-- 20 grand.

699
00:41:59,309 --> 00:42:01,102
Double it.

